Just to put this in perspective, last summer I was reading Mitchell Waldrop=
=E2=80=99s Dream Machine ( https://press.stripe.com/the-dream-machine ) whi=
le I was playing with DV3, as GPT-4 was called then, and it just brought in=
 perspective what this is all about. I think that concept of =E2=80=9CDream=
 Machine=E2=80=9D perhaps best communicates what we have really been doing =
over the last 70 years. All the way starting with what Vannevar Bush wrote =
in his most seminal paper, =E2=80=9CAs We May Think=E2=80=9D, where he had =
all of these concepts like associated memory, or Licklider, who was the fir=
st one to conceptualize the human-computer symbiosis. The Mother of All Dem=
os that came in 68, to the Xerox Alto, and then, of course, the PDC that I =
attended which was the PC Server one in 91. 93 is when we had the Mosaic mo=
ment and then there was iPhone and the Cloud, and all of these would be one=
 continuous journey.

The other thing I=E2=80=99ve always loved is Jobs=E2=80=99 description of c=
omputers as =E2=80=9Cbicycles for the mind=E2=80=9D; it=E2=80=99s sort of a=
 beautiful metaphor that I think captures the essence of what computing is.=
 But then last November we got an upgrade: we went from the bicycle to the =
steam engine with the launch of ChatGPT. It was like the Mosaic moment for =
this generation of the AI platform. Now we look forward as developers to wh=
at we can do going forward. So it=E2=80=99s an exciting time.

It=E2=80=99s obvious why Microsoft would want this to be a moment. AI, spec=
ifically Microsoft=E2=80=99s partnership with OpenAI (which now extends to =
plug-in compatibility between Bing and ChatGPT, and Bing results incorporat=
ed into ChatGPT), is exactly what Microsoft has been searching for since Th=
e End of Windows : a reason to move to the Microsoft ecosystem.

